 (433,8,'7','\r\nYou can use layouts to arrange objects and text on a slide. A layout is one part of a slide master that defines positioning information for content that will later appear on a slide. Layouts contain placeholders (placeholders: Boxes with dotted or hatch-marked borders that are part of most slide layouts. These boxes hold title and body text or objects such as charts, tables, and pictures.), which in turn hold text, such as titles and bulleted lists, and slide content such as SmartArt graphics, tables, charts, pictures, shapes, and clip art (clip art: A single piece of ready-made art, often appearing as a bitmap or a combination of drawn shapes.). While you can add text and object placeholders to a layout or slide master, you cannot add placeholders directly to a slide.\r\n\r\nlayouts themselves just define positioning and formatting for content that will later appear on a slide.\r\n\r\n','129','29/Jun/2017','NC',0,'Computer Science'),
